":"1281","Pawlett, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pawlett, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Picardie, France":"Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paulet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: habitational name from any of several places called Paules in the provinces of Zaragoza and Huesca in Aragon, and Albacete.","Americanized form of Greek   Pavlis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pavlis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Despina, Nikolaos, Vasilios.","Greek: from a derivative of the personal name <i>Pavlos</i> (see   Paul  ), or a shortened form of any of various patronymics derived from this name. Compare   Paules   and   Paulis  .","Czech and Slovak (also <b>Pavliš</b>); Croatian (<b>Pavliš</b>): derivative of the personal name   Pavel   (Slovak commonly <i>Pavol</i>, Croatian commonly <i>Pavao</i>), an equivalent of   Paul  . Compare   Paulis  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir. William Paulet was born in 1185, in Pawlett, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of Lord. Alexander De aunou, of Leigh, Devon, Paulet, Stretchill and Walpole, Somerset. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1209, in Picardie, Fra